    This paper examines the carry trade and when the market moves against it, which the authors call a "currency crash".  They say that currency crashes happen in multiple currencies at the same time and are correlated with a high VIX.  Thus, it seems currency crashes happen when banks are stressed for short-term money.  (Only one has to become stresses, since a hurried unwinding causes a large price movement, which stresses other traders positions, leading to everyone unwinding.)  The VIX data looked good, but I wasn't sold by their study of comovements of currencies.

    The paper has a noteworthy graph on page 19, Figure 5, in the upper-left region.  It shows that after a interest rate movement, the next movement is likely to be soon and in the same direction.  This may be source of profit in uncovered interest parity (UIP).  I think it was from this that they authors concluded that "carry trade activity pushes FX rates towards fundamentals rather than away from it."

    The paper showed traders positions, using open interest in futures.  (The traders seems to be doing well.)

    The authors founds skewness in the returns.  (No surprise.)  Skewness was about equal to that of the stock market.

    The authors found that positive returns held out to periods of 9 months or so.  The best returns were short-term, one or two months long.

