  annote={
    This paper covered the carry trade and the momentum trade.  The momentum trade is: if the carry trade would have been profitable last month, do it this month.  When doing equally-weighted trades in multiple currencies at the same time, both trades have a high Sharpe ratio: 0.89 for carry and 0.62 for momentum.  Combined, the Sharpe ratio is an even higher 0.98.  They compare it to stocks, but didn't appear to measure correlation with stock returns.

   They did not see any skewness.  I find that very odd, but maybe they didn't have many countries near the ZLB.  They did see high kurtosis.

   They explain that the carry trade makes money because the current price is equal to expected value of next month's spot price, but it is not an unbiased estimator.  If the spot price is higher than the future, the carry trade makes money 57\% of the time.  The momentum trade is similar.

   They try to figure out if the carry trade profits are from some risk.  They compare it to a number of them, including "realized stock market volatility", and find only one small interaction.  They use Menkhoff2011's version of FX volatility, but it just seemed to show that high-interest rate currencies move more than low-interest rate ones.

   Section 4 is a discussion of "rare disasters", which seems to be arguing that currency profits are not a risk premium from for "rare disasters".  But a "rare disaster" would be visible in the recorded data, it next measures "peso problems", which are not seen in-sample.  They then use options prices to justify that UIP and CIP carry the same risk, I think.  They conclude that these risks don't explain the profitability of the UIP.

  Section 5 is theory on trading.  I think it says that traders will keep making the trade until the marginal trade is zero profit.  So the prices we see after trading are not profitable, but the ones who already traded are making a profit.  Thus the average trade is profitable, but trading stops.  This seems obvious to me, so I'm not sure why they included it.

  Most data was for 20 currencies, 1976 to 2000.  (They claim 1973 was the start of the post Bretton-Woods era.)  For options, they had 10 currencies from 1995-2009.  
  }
}


